Researching the trading strategy (PETR4) - small profit fast mean reversion¶

Amost all is based on the book Advances in Financial Machine Learning

    https://www.amazon.com/Advances-Financial-Machine-Learning-Marcos/dp/1119482089

Money bars (Chapter 2) and most of data manipulations (indicators etc.) done in a C++ dll.

  • The Dll
    • uses CTalib for tecnical indicators
    • uses PytorchCpp (Uses GPU) for fracdiff indicator (Chapter 4)
    • uses BoostC++ for circular_buffer (all tick/bars buffers used)
    • has a python-interpreter embedded
    • can call any Python script passing C++ data by the grace of pybind11 stl header library
      • the fastest possible way to use Python Metatrader (ref. missing)
    • also due pybind11 is also a python module incbars.pyd (Python API)
      • can call exactly the same code Metatrader calls
    • why same C++ dll with a Python API?
      • Fastest way I imagined to research & deploy machine learning ideas
    • is already tested[1] and works well within Metatrader 5 (tick based on real ticks backtest)
      • [1]more tests should / must be written (I'm using C++ Google Tests unit testing)

For researching porpouses the python module incbars.pyd is used. The entire 2019 tick data for PETR4 is available/used.

The strategy¶

Using specific values - but all parameters can be set when calling C++

  • buy or sell based on 6 bollinger bands signals on money bars
    • buy when crossing bellow the lower band 1
    • sell when crossing above the upper band -1
  • money bars are formed for each 500k negotiated (tick analyses)
  • try to profit in 15 minutes (expire time) or leave
  • sl is 100 tp is 50
  • use tripple-barrier for labelling (Chapter 3)
    • training samples are labelled 1
      • when profit >= tp or profit >= tp/2 at expire time
      • 0 when failed
  • use event and previous 9 m.bars to form training features e. g.
    • number of ticks to form a money bar
    • time to ... .....
    • etc.
  • use a extra tree classifier to predict based on signal features
    • if it is a valid entry

working on...¶

  • Purging from the training samples information overlapping with testing samples
  • Implement sample weights based on average uniqueness of sample

Turned in two binary problems?¶

Two classifiers one for -1 and other for +1¶

Or One binary problem?¶

  • One vs all approach
  • Better have two models independend than one
    Though the outcome can be classified for 1 or 0 - sucess or failure -
    the origin for each of the class 'I believe' are independent.
    Better use 2 classifiers.
    Than one model trying to learn 2 different classes not known to be correlated
  • Or better have one model with more training samples?
  • I will seek for the best accuracy for the class 0
    • that is the one responsible for making us loosing money

In [326]:
# concurrent labels at each xy pair index 
clabels = np.zeros(foldsize)
avgunique = np.zeros(foldsize)
for i in range(foldsize):
    samples_conc = ((sxyinfo[i,0]>=sxyinfo[:, 0])&(sxyinfo[i,0]<=sxyinfo[:, 1]))
    clabels[i] = np.sum(samples_conc)    

for i in range(foldsize):
    samples_conc = ((sxyinfo[i,0]>=sxyinfo[:, 0])&(sxyinfo[i,0]<=sxyinfo[:, 1]))
    avgunique[i] = np.mean((1./clabels)[samples_conc])

avgunique[:80]  = np.nan # 'ignoring' first
    
# will be needed to be scaled 
sweight = avgunique*np.abs(lbsigns['ret'][:foldsize])

neval=5 # next 5 entries  after Expert_Delay_Time will be used for scoring the model

for group in progressbar(df.groupby('idxt')):
    group = group[1].copy()   # remove warning    
    idxt= group.iloc[0, 0]
    idxs = idxt+folds.ntrain
    idxe = idxs+folds.npred
    group['yscore'] = y[idxs:idxe] # fill in yscore truth values
    group = group[ group['dt'].values >  ]
    group['acc'] = None
    group['neval'] = neval
    group['ypredpbm'] = None
    group['dtfst'] = None
    group['dtlst'] = None
    group = group[group.valid].drop_duplicates(['dt']) # drop entry same time (kind'a random)
    if len(group) > 0:
        valid_ypred = group['ypred'].values[:neval].astype(int)
        valid_yscore = group['yscore'].values[:neval].astype(int)
        valid_ypredp = group['ypredpb'].values[:neval]
        cm = confusion_matrix(valid_yscore, valid_ypred)
        if cm.shape[0] < 2: # case only 1 class on both vectors
            acc =  1 if (np.unique(valid_yscore) == np.unique(valid_ypred)) else 0
        else:
            acc = cm[0, 0]/(cm[0, 0]+cm[1, 0]) # for class 0 what matters
        neval = len(valid_ypred)
        group['acc'] = acc
        group['neval'] = neval
        group['ypredpbm'] = np.mean(valid_ypredp)
        group['dtfst'] = group['dt'].iloc[0] # first 
        group['dtlst'] = group['dt'].iloc[neval-1] # last time of prediction
        dfnew = dfnew.append(group, sort=False)
